#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:5
msgid "Writing custom array containers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:7
msgid ""
"Numpy's dispatch mechanism, introduced in numpy version v1.16 is the "
"recommended approach for writing custom N-dimensional array containers that "
"are compatible with the numpy API and provide custom implementations of "
"numpy functionality. Applications include `dask <https://docs.dask.org/en/"
"stable/>`_ arrays, an N-dimensional array distributed across multiple nodes, "
"and `cupy <https://docs-cupy.chainer.org/en/stable/>`_ arrays, an N-"
"dimensional array on a GPU."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:15
msgid ""
"To get a feel for writing custom array containers, we'll begin with a simple "
"example that has rather narrow utility but illustrates the concepts involved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:32
msgid "Our custom array can be instantiated like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:38
msgid ""
"We can convert to a numpy array using :func:`numpy.array` or :func:`numpy."
"asarray`, which will call its ``__array__`` method to obtain a standard "
"``numpy.ndarray``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:49
msgid ""
"The ``__array__`` method can optionally accept a `dtype` argument. If "
"provided, this argument specifies the desired data type for the resulting "
"NumPy array. Your implementation should attempt to convert the data to this "
"`dtype` if possible. If the conversion is not supported, it's generally best "
"to fall back to a default type or raise a `TypeError` or `ValueError`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:55
msgid "Here's an example demonstrating its use with `dtype` specification:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:64
msgid ""
"If we operate on ``arr`` with a numpy function, numpy will again use the "
"``__array__`` interface to convert it to an array and then apply the "
"function in the usual way."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:76
msgid "Notice that the return type is a standard ``numpy.ndarray``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:81
msgid ""
"How can we pass our custom array type through this function? Numpy allows a "
"class to indicate that it would like to handle computations in a custom-"
"defined way through the interfaces ``__array_ufunc__`` and "
"``__array_function__``. Let's take one at a time, starting with "
"``__array_ufunc__``. This method covers :ref:`ufuncs`, a class of functions "
"that includes, for example, :func:`numpy.multiply` and :func:`numpy.sin`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:88
msgid "The ``__array_ufunc__`` receives:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:90
msgid "``ufunc``, a function like ``numpy.multiply``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:91
msgid ""
"``method``, a string, differentiating between ``numpy.multiply(...)`` and "
"variants like ``numpy.multiply.outer``, ``numpy.multiply.accumulate``, and "
"so on.  For the common case, ``numpy.multiply(...)``, ``method == "
"'__call__'``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:94
msgid "``inputs``, which could be a mixture of different types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:95
msgid "``kwargs``, keyword arguments passed to the function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:97
msgid "For this example we will only handle the method ``__call__``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:132
msgid "Now our custom array type passes through numpy functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:142
msgid "At this point ``arr + 3`` does not work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:149
msgid ""
"To support it, we need to define the Python interfaces ``__add__``, "
"``__lt__``, and so on to dispatch to the corresponding ufunc. We can achieve "
"this conveniently by inheriting from the mixin :class:`~numpy.lib.mixins."
"NDArrayOperatorsMixin`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:193
msgid ""
"Now let's tackle ``__array_function__``. We'll create dict that maps numpy "
"functions to our custom variants."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:239
msgid ""
"A convenient pattern is to define a decorator ``implements`` that can be "
"used to add functions to ``HANDLED_FUNCTIONS``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:250
msgid ""
"Now we write implementations of numpy functions for ``DiagonalArray``. For "
"completeness, to support the usage ``arr.sum()`` add a method ``sum`` that "
"calls ``numpy.sum(self)``, and the same for ``mean``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:270
msgid ""
"If the user tries to use any numpy functions not included in "
"``HANDLED_FUNCTIONS``, a ``TypeError`` will be raised by numpy, indicating "
"that this operation is not supported. For example, concatenating two "
"``DiagonalArrays`` does not produce another diagonal array, so it is not "
"supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:281
msgid ""
"Additionally, our implementations of ``sum`` and ``mean`` do not accept the "
"optional arguments that numpy's implementation does."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:290
msgid ""
"The user always has the option of converting to a normal ``numpy.ndarray`` "
"with :func:`numpy.asarray` and using standard numpy from there."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:306
msgid ""
"The implementation of ``DiagonalArray`` in this example only handles the "
"``np.sum`` and ``np.mean`` functions for brevity. Many other functions in "
"the Numpy API are also available to wrap and a full-fledged custom array "
"container can explicitly support all functions that Numpy makes available to "
"wrap."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:311
msgid ""
"Numpy provides some utilities to aid testing of custom array containers that "
"implement the ``__array_ufunc__`` and ``__array_function__`` protocols in "
"the ``numpy.testing.overrides`` namespace."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:315
msgid ""
"To check if a Numpy function can be overridden via ``__array_ufunc__``, you "
"can use :func:`~numpy.testing.overrides.allows_array_ufunc_override`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:322
msgid ""
"Similarly, you can check if a function can be overridden via "
"``__array_function__`` using :func:`~numpy.testing.overrides."
"allows_array_function_override`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:326
msgid ""
"Lists of every overridable function in the Numpy API are also available via :"
"func:`~numpy.testing.overrides.get_overridable_numpy_array_functions` for "
"functions that support the ``__array_function__`` protocol and :func:`~numpy."
"testing.overrides.get_overridable_numpy_ufuncs` for functions that support "
"the ``__array_ufunc__`` protocol. Both functions return sets of functions "
"that are present in the Numpy public API. User-defined ufuncs or ufuncs "
"defined in other libraries that depend on Numpy are not present in these "
"sets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../user/basics.dispatch.rst:335
msgid ""
"Refer to the `dask source code <https://github.com/dask/dask>`_ and `cupy "
"source code <https://github.com/cupy/cupy>`_  for more fully-worked examples "
"of custom array containers."
msgstr ""

